The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Munnabhai arrest in college
                                                                                                               Munnabhai arrest in college
          TAPAS CHAKRABORTY                              
	Lucknow, Jan. 28: Munnabhai, the screen thug who hugged to heal, forced a doctor to write his exam so that he could pursue an MBBS. Now, many seem to be embracing his ways.        
	A third-year student of a prestigious Lucknow medical college was arrested today for allegedly posing as a candidate to write an MBBS entrance test of a Punjab institute.        
	Arj Kumar, picked up from King George Medical Colleges hostel this afternoon, is said to be part of a medical entrance scam involving 24 MBBS students from Uttar Pradesh, Bihar and Delhi. The 21-year-old from Varanasi is one of three said to be involved from his college and nine from other medical colleges in the state.        
	Arj and others were said to have taken sums ranging from Rs 50,000 to Rs 3 lakh for posing as dummy candidates in last Junes exams conducted by Baba Farid University of Health Sciences in Punjabs Faridkot.        
	Arj, identified from the exam halls CCTV images, is a bright student and hails from Varanasi, said Uttar Pradesh police.                          
	, which helped a visiting Punjab police team round him up. Of the other two from his college alleged to be part of the racket, a girl is absconding while another boy may be arrested anytime, the police said.        
	Lucknow additional police superintendent Pares Pandey said Arj had admitted being a dummy candidate for money. Dr Sarooj Chooramani Gopal, vice-chancellor of King George Medical Collegesaid he had promised Punjab police full cooperation in the bust-up.        
	The scandal broke last July, when it emerged that dummies like Arj, hired by students from affluent families, were part of the over 8,000 candidates to have taken the Punjab test. Many of the other dummies were from medical colleges in Bhagalpur and Patna in Bihar, Aligarh in Uttar Pradesh and Delhi, the police said, adding efforts were under way to identify and arrest them.        
	The number of those taking Munnabhai too seriously in the Uttar Pradesh capital has been growing, but revelations about the new scandal have come at a time Sanjay Dutt has declared himself a Samajwadi Party candidate for the Lucknow Lok Sabha seat. The Munnabhai films are among Dutts most popular.        
	In 2002, several King George students, and a professor, were found involved in an entrance test for AIIMS. Later, another student from the city was arrested for allegedly appearing as a dummy candidate for a medical college in Madhya Pradesh.         
	Many of them were alleged to have been hired and paid by coaching centres in Patna, Delhi and other places to appear for the candidates they had groomed, the police said.                                                                                                                                                                           
